NATION BRIEFS																																												 Bangalore, Nov. 23: A man who promised an NGO central funds by posing as Sonia Gandhis secretary was held after a Congress MLA saw through his game.																																												
	Chennais Gunashekhar Pillai, 54, who introduced himself as Shekhar Pillai, was flown from Delhi last night by Appaji Gowda, the NGOs head. He told the NGO boss that he would help get the funds sanctioned, in return for a small commission, when MLA D.K. Shivakumar, Gowdas friend, got suspicious and called up Delhi.																																												Melbourne (PTI): An Indian student has been sentenced to two years in jail for molesting a nine-year-old at a shopping centre. Mohammad Sehnawaz Khan, 31, had lured the girl into a change room on the pretext of trying on clothes he wanted to send to his niece in India.																																												Kozhikode (PTI): The Indian embassy in UAE is working out a comprehensive scheme, including a grievance redressal mechanism, for the welfare of Indians living there. It wants to reform the entire process of contracting and look into the issue of female household workers, ambassador Talmiz Ahmad said.																																												Jalgaon (PTI): The car of Bhusawals sub-divisional officer was allegedly set on fire on Thursday. Fire-fighting tenders doused the flames but the vehicle was completely gutted, police said. A search is on for the culprits.																																												New Delhi (PTI): Britains visa authority has identified 140 Indian companies which provided bogus employment references for visa applicants till 2006-07, a study revealed on Friday. Consultancy firms Economist Intelligence Unit and Integrascreen had jointly undertaken the study.																																												 Chennai (PTI): A 25-year-old man stabbed his mother for not allowing him to stay along with her and his step-sisters, police said. Nagaraj is now behind bars and his mother has been hospitalised.
